On September 29, 2017, President Donald J. Trump issued a Presidential Determination on Refugee Admissions for Fiscal Year 2018. The President authorized the admission of up to 45,000 refugees to the United States, citing humanitarian concerns and national interest. The admissions will be allocated among different regions, with Africa receiving 19,000, East Asia receiving 5,000, Europe and Central Asia receiving 2,000, Latin America/Caribbean receiving 1,500, and Near East/South Asia receiving 17,500. The President also specified that certain persons in Cuba, Eurasia and the Baltics, Iraq, Honduras, Guatemala, El Salvador, and those identified by a United States Embassy in exceptional circumstances may be considered refugees for admission to the United States. The determination will be published in the Federal Register.